Phase 1: Environment & Architecture Planning
Step 1: Understand the data flow first
Before writing a single line of code, map out the pipeline mentally:
PDF Input → Parser → [Text chunks + Images] → Embeddings → Vector DB → Query → Retriever → VLM → Answer
Step 2: Set up your environment

Create a Python virtual environment (Python 3.10+ recommended)
You'll need these tool categories: a PDF parser, an embedding model, a vector database client, and a VLM inference engine
Decide early whether you're running the VLM locally (needs a decent GPU, 8GB+ VRAM) or via a hosted API (easier to start, costs money). For a side project, start with a hosted or quantized local model.


Phase 2: PDF Parsing — Splitting Text from Images
Step 3: Choose your PDF parser
This is the most underrated step. Use PyMuPDF (fitz) — it's the most reliable for extracting both text blocks and embedded images with their page numbers and bounding boxes. pdfplumber is a decent alternative for text-heavy docs.
Step 4: Extract text with context
Don't just dump all text into one blob. Extract it per page or per logical block, and always store the page number as metadata. This is what lets you later say "page 42" and mean it.
Step 5: Extract images
For each page, extract embedded images and save them as individual files (PNG/JPEG). Crucially, tag each image with:

Page number
Position on page (x, y coordinates)
A generated filename like page_042_img_1.png

Step 6: Handle "text near images"
This is the secret sauce. For each extracted image, also grab the text surrounding it on the same page (caption text, nearby paragraphs). Store this as the image's "context text." It dramatically improves retrieval accuracy later.

Phase 3: Building the Embedding Pipeline
Step 7: Embed your text chunks
Use a standard text embedding model (OpenAI text-embedding-3-small, or open-source sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2). Each chunk becomes a vector. Store it with metadata: {page, chunk_id, text_content}.
Step 8: Embed your images with CLIP
This is the core VLM-specific step. CLIP (from OpenAI, available via HuggingFace as openai/clip-vit-base-patch32) is a model that embeds both images and text into the same vector space. This is what makes multimodal search possible.

Load CLIP's image processor and model
For each extracted image, run it through CLIP's vision encoder → you get a 512-dim (or 768-dim) vector
Store it with metadata: {page, image_path, context_text}

Step 9: Understand why CLIP matters here
When a user later asks "what's on the wiring diagram on page 42?", you can embed that text query through CLIP's text encoder and it will be geometrically close to the wiring diagram's image vector. That's the magic — the shared embedding space.

Phase 4: Setting Up the Vector Database
Step 10: Choose and run Qdrant
Go with Qdrant — it's easier to run locally via Docker and has excellent Python support. Spin it up with one Docker command.
Step 11: Create two separate collections

text_chunks collection — for your text embeddings
image_chunks collection — for your CLIP image embeddings

Keep them separate because they have different vector dimensions and different metadata schemas.
Step 12: Upload your vectors
Batch-insert all your text vectors and image vectors into their respective collections. Every point in Qdrant must have: a unique ID, the vector itself, and a payload (the metadata JSON you prepared earlier).

Phase 5: The Retrieval Logic
Step 13: Build a hybrid retriever
When a user asks a question, you run two parallel searches:

Embed the question with your text model → search the text_chunks collection
Embed the question with CLIP's text encoder → search the image_chunks collection

Step 14: Merge and rank the results
You'll get back, say, top-3 text chunks and top-2 images. Combine them into a single context payload. You can do simple score-based merging for a side project — just take everything above a similarity threshold.
Step 15: Assemble the context package
Your final retrieved context for the VLM should contain:

The relevant text chunks (as strings)
The relevant images (as file paths or base64-encoded data)
Page numbers for traceability


Phase 6: VLM Inference
Step 16: Choose your VLM wisely
For a side project, your best options are:

LLaVA-1.5-7B — battle-tested, runs on ~10GB VRAM, great HuggingFace support
Qwen-VL-Chat — excellent at document understanding, slightly heavier
moondream2 — very lightweight (~2GB), good for resource-constrained setups
GPT-4o via API — easiest integration if you don't want local inference headaches

Step 17: Structure your VLM prompt carefully
The prompt you send to the VLM should have a clear structure:
System: You are a technical manual assistant. Answer only based on the provided context.

Context Text: [retrieved text chunks here]

[Attach retrieved images here]

User Question: [the actual user question]
The instruction to answer only from context is critical — otherwise the VLM will hallucinate from its training data.
Step 18: Handle the image input format
Most VLMs accept images as base64-encoded strings in the message payload (similar to GPT-4 Vision format). Convert your retrieved image files to base64 before sending them to the model.

Phase 7: Wiring It All Together with LangChain/LlamaIndex
Step 19: Use LlamaIndex if you're focused on RAG
LlamaIndex has first-class RAG abstractions. It's more opinionated but saves a lot of boilerplate. LangChain is more flexible but requires more manual wiring. For this specific project, LlamaIndex is the better fit.
Step 20: Build a custom retriever node
Wrap your Qdrant dual-search logic (Step 13–15) as a custom BaseRetriever in LlamaIndex. This lets you plug it into the standard query pipeline cleanly.
Step 21: Build a custom query engine
Chain: User Query → Custom Retriever → Context Assembler → VLM → Response. LlamaIndex's CustomQueryEngine base class is perfect for this.

Phase 8: Evaluation & Iteration
Step 22: Test with a real dense PDF first
Don't test with a simple 10-page PDF. Grab an actual engineering manual or technical datasheet (many are public). The complexity will immediately expose weaknesses in your parser and retriever.
Step 23: Evaluate retrieval quality separately from generation quality
These are two different problems. First confirm your retriever is pulling the right pages/images for a given question (you can check this manually). Only then debug the VLM's answer quality.
Step 24: Add metadata filtering as a power feature
Since you store page numbers, let users optionally say "only look at pages 40–50". Qdrant supports payload filtering during search — this is a huge UX win for large manuals.
